\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {4}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Composition Inflation Theorem: $T(n,d) = d\,(d+1)^{n-1}$ counts distinguishable labeled timing trajectories and grows exponentially in both the number of events $n$ and the dimension $d$.} (\textbf  {A}) $T(n,d)$ versus $n$ on a logarithmic axis for $d = 1,\ldots  ,6$ (coloured lines). Each series is linear on the log scale, confirming the exponential growth law; the slope $(d+1)$ increases with $d$, spanning seven decades over $n = 1$ to $11$. (\textbf  {B}) Three-dimensional surface of $\log _{10} T(n,d)$ over the grid $n \in [1,10]$, $d \in [1,8]$. The surface rises steeply in both dimensions; the curvature in $d$ reflects the $(d+1)^{n-1}$ factor compounding with $d$. (\textbf  {C}) Growth ratio $T(n,d)/T(n{-}1,d)$ versus $n$ for $d = 2,\ldots  ,6$. Dashed horizontal lines at $d{+}1$ confirm that the ratio is constant and equal to $d{+}1$ for all $n \geq 2$, providing direct numerical verification of the recurrence relation $T(n,d) = (d{+}1)\,T(n{-}1,d)$. (\textbf  {D}) Direct enumeration versus closed-form formula for $d = 3$, $n = 1,\ldots  ,7$ (blue and red bars, log scale). The enumeration sums $d^k$ over all integer compositions of $n$ into $k$ parts; the formula $T(n,3) = 3 \cdot 4^{n-1}$ matches exactly, with bars overlapping at every value of $n$.}}{9}{figure.caption.5}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:composition_inflation}{{4}{9}{\textbf {Composition Inflation Theorem: $T(n,d) = d\,(d+1)^{n-1}$ counts distinguishable labeled timing trajectories and grows exponentially in both the number of events $n$ and the dimension $d$.} (\textbf {A}) $T(n,d)$ versus $n$ on a logarithmic axis for $d = 1,\ldots ,6$ (coloured lines). Each series is linear on the log scale, confirming the exponential growth law; the slope $(d+1)$ increases with $d$, spanning seven decades over $n = 1$ to $11$. (\textbf {B}) Three-dimensional surface of $\log _{10} T(n,d)$ over the grid $n \in [1,10]$, $d \in [1,8]$. The surface rises steeply in both dimensions; the curvature in $d$ reflects the $(d+1)^{n-1}$ factor compounding with $d$. (\textbf {C}) Growth ratio $T(n,d)/T(n{-}1,d)$ versus $n$ for $d = 2,\ldots ,6$. Dashed horizontal lines at $d{+}1$ confirm that the ratio is constant and equal to $d{+}1$ for all $n \geq 2$, providing direct numerical verification of the recurrence relation $T(n,d) = (d{+}1)\,T(n{-}1,d)$. (\textbf {D}) Direct enumeration versus closed-form formula for $d = 3$, $n = 1,\ldots ,7$ (blue and red bars, log scale). The enumeration sums $d^k$ over all integer compositions of $n$ into $k$ parts; the formula $T(n,3) = 3 \cdot 4^{n-1}$ matches exactly, with bars overlapping at every value of $n$}{figure.caption.5}{}}
