\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {5}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Monotone Time Coordinate and Structural Replay Resistance: $M(k)$ is non-decreasing by construction, and any replayed signal produces a $\Delta P$ distinguishable from the original.} (\textbf  {A}) Monotone counter $M(k)$ versus signal index $k$ (blue staircase with shaded area). Increments are drawn from $\{0,1,2\}$ at each step; the sequence is non-decreasing throughout, illustrating the constitutive asymmetry $t = M/f$ that forbids time reversal. (\textbf  {B}) Timing deviation $\Delta P(k) = T_{\mathrm  {ref}}(k) - t_{\mathrm  {received}}(k)$ versus signal index. The signal fluctuates around zero with sub-cycle jitter; the shaded area tracks the sign of each deviation, providing the raw datum processed by timing cells. (\textbf  {C}) Three-dimensional trajectory $(k,\,M_k,\,\Delta P_k)$ in trajectory space. Red dots mark every tenth sample; the path is monotone in $M$ regardless of $\Delta P$ sign, confirming that no trajectory can reverse its $M$-coordinate. (\textbf  {D}) Scatter of replayed $\Delta P$ versus original $\Delta P$ for 300 signal pairs. All replay values are shifted upward by a random delay $\delta \in [0.18,\,0.75]$~s, placing every point above the identity diagonal (dashed). A replayed signal is thus mapped to a different cell than the original, making the instruction structurally unexecutable.}}{10}{figure.caption.6}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:monotone_replay}{{5}{10}{\textbf {Monotone Time Coordinate and Structural Replay Resistance: $M(k)$ is non-decreasing by construction, and any replayed signal produces a $\Delta P$ distinguishable from the original.} (\textbf {A}) Monotone counter $M(k)$ versus signal index $k$ (blue staircase with shaded area). Increments are drawn from $\{0,1,2\}$ at each step; the sequence is non-decreasing throughout, illustrating the constitutive asymmetry $t = M/f$ that forbids time reversal. (\textbf {B}) Timing deviation $\Delta P(k) = T_{\mathrm {ref}}(k) - t_{\mathrm {received}}(k)$ versus signal index. The signal fluctuates around zero with sub-cycle jitter; the shaded area tracks the sign of each deviation, providing the raw datum processed by timing cells. (\textbf {C}) Three-dimensional trajectory $(k,\,M_k,\,\Delta P_k)$ in trajectory space. Red dots mark every tenth sample; the path is monotone in $M$ regardless of $\Delta P$ sign, confirming that no trajectory can reverse its $M$-coordinate. (\textbf {D}) Scatter of replayed $\Delta P$ versus original $\Delta P$ for 300 signal pairs. All replay values are shifted upward by a random delay $\delta \in [0.18,\,0.75]$~s, placing every point above the identity diagonal (dashed). A replayed signal is thus mapped to a different cell than the original, making the instruction structurally unexecutable}{figure.caption.6}{}}
