\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {7}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Multi-Domain Transduction: temperature, pressure, and light sensors each produce a scalar $\Delta P$ through domain-specific oscillator circuits, enabling composition of heterogeneous physical signals in a unified timing space.} (\textbf  {A}) TCXO frequency deviation $\Delta P$ (in parts per million) versus ambient temperature over the industrial range $[-40,\,+85]$\,°C. The parabolic response $\Delta f/f \propto (T - T_0)^2$ maps the full temperature domain to a bounded $\Delta P$ interval, with the minimum at the turnover temperature $T_0 = 25$\,°C. (\textbf  {B}) MEMS capacitive-to-timing delay $\Delta P$ (in nanoseconds) versus barometric pressure. The response is linear over $[0,\,1013]$\,hPa via the RC relation $\Delta \tau = R\,\Delta C(P)$, demonstrating monotone pressure-to-timing transduction. (\textbf  {C}) Three-dimensional $\Delta P$ point cloud for 600 simultaneous readings across temperature ($\Delta P_T$), pressure ($\Delta P_P$), and photodiode-RC ($\Delta P_L$) channels. Points are coloured by Euclidean distance from the origin; the cloud occupies a compact region confirming that all three dimensions are jointly bounded. (\textbf  {D}) Density-normalised histograms of $\Delta P$ from four sensor types (TCXO, MEMS, RC-photodiode, piezo-vibration) overlaid on a common axis. Despite different physical origins, all distributions are centred near zero with characteristic widths, making them directly composable via the $D$-dimensional S-entropy framework.}}{13}{figure.caption.9}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:multidomain}{{7}{13}{\textbf {Multi-Domain Transduction: temperature, pressure, and light sensors each produce a scalar $\Delta P$ through domain-specific oscillator circuits, enabling composition of heterogeneous physical signals in a unified timing space.} (\textbf {A}) TCXO frequency deviation $\Delta P$ (in parts per million) versus ambient temperature over the industrial range $[-40,\,+85]$\,°C. The parabolic response $\Delta f/f \propto (T - T_0)^2$ maps the full temperature domain to a bounded $\Delta P$ interval, with the minimum at the turnover temperature $T_0 = 25$\,°C. (\textbf {B}) MEMS capacitive-to-timing delay $\Delta P$ (in nanoseconds) versus barometric pressure. The response is linear over $[0,\,1013]$\,hPa via the RC relation $\Delta \tau = R\,\Delta C(P)$, demonstrating monotone pressure-to-timing transduction. (\textbf {C}) Three-dimensional $\Delta P$ point cloud for 600 simultaneous readings across temperature ($\Delta P_T$), pressure ($\Delta P_P$), and photodiode-RC ($\Delta P_L$) channels. Points are coloured by Euclidean distance from the origin; the cloud occupies a compact region confirming that all three dimensions are jointly bounded. (\textbf {D}) Density-normalised histograms of $\Delta P$ from four sensor types (TCXO, MEMS, RC-photodiode, piezo-vibration) overlaid on a common axis. Despite different physical origins, all distributions are centred near zero with characteristic widths, making them directly composable via the $D$-dimensional S-entropy framework}{figure.caption.9}{}}
\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {8}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Structural Incorruptibility: absence of a payload parser eliminates arbitrary code injection; the attack surface is a finite, pre-compiled cell-to-action map with zero novel-action capacity.} (\textbf  {A}) Log-scale density histogram of 100\,000 adversarial payload sizes drawn from an exponential distribution with mean 500 bytes. Payloads span three decades; the log-scale axis reveals the heavy-tailed structure representative of real-world injection attempts. (\textbf  {B}) Bar chart of input counts across five attack categories (noise, malformed, oversized, bad-tag, valid~$\Delta P$). The black legend entry ``novel actions $= 0$'' confirms that across all 100\,000 inputs, no action outside the pre-compiled cell-action map was executed. (\textbf  {C}) Three-dimensional surface of detection latency (in clock cycles) over the joint attack parameter space (payload size $\times $ pattern complexity). The surface is flat at approximately one cycle across the entire domain, demonstrating $\mathcal  {O}(1)$ rejection regardless of payload size or structural complexity. (\textbf  {D}) Density-normalised histograms of $\Delta P$ measured during benign operation (blue) and under active adversarial injection (red). The two distributions are indistinguishable, confirming that payload content exerts no influence on timing behaviour: the attack channel and the signal channel are structurally disjoint.}}{13}{figure.caption.12}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:incorruptibility}{{8}{13}{\textbf {Structural Incorruptibility: absence of a payload parser eliminates arbitrary code injection; the attack surface is a finite, pre-compiled cell-to-action map with zero novel-action capacity.} (\textbf {A}) Log-scale density histogram of 100\,000 adversarial payload sizes drawn from an exponential distribution with mean 500 bytes. Payloads span three decades; the log-scale axis reveals the heavy-tailed structure representative of real-world injection attempts. (\textbf {B}) Bar chart of input counts across five attack categories (noise, malformed, oversized, bad-tag, valid~$\Delta P$). The black legend entry ``novel actions $= 0$'' confirms that across all 100\,000 inputs, no action outside the pre-compiled cell-action map was executed. (\textbf {C}) Three-dimensional surface of detection latency (in clock cycles) over the joint attack parameter space (payload size $\times $ pattern complexity). The surface is flat at approximately one cycle across the entire domain, demonstrating $\mathcal {O}(1)$ rejection regardless of payload size or structural complexity. (\textbf {D}) Density-normalised histograms of $\Delta P$ measured during benign operation (blue) and under active adversarial injection (red). The two distributions are indistinguishable, confirming that payload content exerts no influence on timing behaviour: the attack channel and the signal channel are structurally disjoint}{figure.caption.12}{}}
